Final answer: [Deny]

Value I’d give up: 2 Ore = 2 × 35 = 70  
Value I’d receive: 5 Wheat + 3 Wood = 5 × 5 + 3 × 11 = 25 + 33 = 58  

Net value change: 58 – 70 = –12 (I lose value).

Since 58 < 70, I will decline this offer and craft a counter-proposal that improves my deck.

Current deck (after the first trade in which I gained 3 Wheat + 2 Wood, losing 1 Ore):
- Wheat: 15 – 0 + 3 = 18  
- Wood: 18 – 0 + 2 = 20  
- Sheep: 18  
- Brick: 21  
- Ore: 9 – 1 = 8  

I have an excess of Wheat (18 @ 5) and Wood (20 @ 11) and a shortage of high-value Brick @ 28.  
I’ll offer a bundle of 6 Wheat + 4 Wood, whose total value is 6×5 + 4×11 = 30 + 44 = 74 — enough to fairly request 2 Brick (2×28 = 56) plus a small “premium” of 1 Sheep (17).  
For me this is a gain of 73 – 74 = –1 (essentially break even to me), yet it trims my least-valuable surplus and brings me two desperately-needed Brick, a trade I’m willing to make.

[Offer: 6 Wheat, 4 Wood -> 2 Brick, 1 Sheep]
